North Korea Says ‘No Thinking’ to Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were exacerbating mistrust of the United States and that there was no way for the country to unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as the discontinuation of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear test center and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
“However, we don’t see any corresponding U.S. response,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way we can proceed to our disarmament first.”
While Ri has recycled already known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it made gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in that they do not preliminarily reject unilateral denuclearization, in contrast to Pyongyang’s earlier positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever held between an incumbent U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump offered security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States claims that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal coercively, opposing until the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who don’t know anything about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of sanctions is exacerbating our suspicion.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the US leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the stakeholder in this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that steering North Korea’s rockets toward U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Bad President” Trump called Kim “the rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year had threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said much remained to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until the denuclearization of North Korea.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a calendar for this, noting that “if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously until denuclearization is complete, final and verifiable.”
The Security Council unanimously reinforced sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to strangle funding for North Korea’s nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later declared that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, although North Korea later denounced him for "making gangster demands.
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile installation and also a nuclear complex if the United States "takes corresponding measures".
Pompeo said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" they were seeking were the security guarantees Trump took in Singapore, as well as initiatives to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course that teaches them to rest enough
A new course at Harvard University this year put all its students to sleep more, in an initiative to fight the male culture of studying in caffeine-infused “directs.”
One professor concluded that students at this university at the top of the world rankings often had no idea about the most basic concepts of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
The inspiration for the course came after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why are you just telling me this in the last year of the course?'
She said no one had ever mentioned to her the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains to students the essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the institution decided to introduce the course after it concluded that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to pick up to bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it won’t change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as we all have a right to know the health effects of the smoking option,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “doing it straight” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we get enough quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid fattening, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of physical biology and chemistry, helped Professor Czeisler conceive the course after attending one of his classes last year in his first year at Harvard.
