This allows users to decide where their data is stored and who has access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokingly stated that the underlying intent of Inrupt is to “dominate the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said about the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own “personal online data warehouse,” or POD.
This may contain contact lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available in a single browser and simultaneously.
What is unique about the personal online data warehouse is that it is exclusively up to the user to decide who has access to what type of information.
The company calls it “personal training through data.”
Inrupt’s idea, according to company CEO John Bruce, is to provide the right resources, processes and skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company is currently comprised of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some in-house programmers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology creators around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a total change in which all of their business models are reversed overnight.
“We’re not asking for permission.”
In a Medium post on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to create commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web created with Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on Internet neutrality.
Even while launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this upcoming era of the Web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: Tribute to the cleric decorated with the Victoria Cross in the First Great War
The only cleric of the Church of England to receive the Victoria Cross during the First Great War as a fighter was honored in his hometown after 100 years.
Reverend Lieutenant Colonel Bernard Vann was awarded the award on 29 September 1918 with the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew he received the highest British military honor.
His two grandchildren unveiled a commemorative plaque at a stop in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of them, Michael Vann, said it was "brilliantly symbolic" that the plaque had been presented exactly 100 years after the feat that gave the decoration to his grandfather.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion on the crossing of the Saint-Quentin Canal "in a very thick fog and under closed fire of portable weapons and machine guns".
Then he ran to the line of fire and, "with the utmost courage," led the line forward before attacking alone a cannon and shooting down three detachment soldiers.
Lieutenant-Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s acts were “something I know I would never be able to match, but also a lesson in humility.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, deposited a wreath after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he was "very honored to participate in the parade" and added that "the courage of a genuine hero is being demonstrated through the support that will be given by many people."
