New German warship once again postponed
The German navy's latest frigate should have entered service in 2014 to replace Cold War-time warships. However, it will have to wait until at least next year due to systems prone to failure and an exponentially growing cost, according to local media.
The entry into service of the "Rheinland-Pfalz," the command ship of the newest frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a military spokesman.
The vessel should have joined the navy in 2014, but the disturbing post-delivery problems undermined the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg class vessels that the navy had ordered in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen class frigates.
It is known that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, in addition to a number of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies such as the reduction of radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer periods between maintenance, which would allow the latest frigates to be sent on missions lasting up to two years away from the ports of origin.
However, continued delays have meant that with state-of-the-art warships, considered a way for Germany to project power across borders, they will already be outdated when they enter service, Die Zeit reports.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German navy refused to put it into service and returned it to Blohm & Voss shipyards in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cite a number of crucial "hardware and software defects" that would make the warship useless if used on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly important, since the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half of the contingent needed in the oldest frigates of the Bremen class.
It was also known that the vessel is excessively heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the ability of the navy to install additional functionality in the future.
The 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is thought to have twice the weight of ships of similar classes used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the price of the entire project, including crew training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros, an increase from the 2.2 billion initially budgeted.
The problems afflicting the most recent frigates have become particularly important in light of recent warnings that German naval power is weakening.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliamentary defence committee, acknowledged that the navy is currently running out of ships capable of being used.
The problem has grown exponentially over time, as older ships have been put out of service without any vessels to replace them.
In the end, he regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class were able to join the navy.
National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
Further research is underway on a property in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape to look for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behavior of these singular flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and fruit bats, as well as long-eared browns and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations scattered around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all recordings will assess the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A map of the habitat will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviors at the territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, expects the results to reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as meadow breeding, as well as how best to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development work that affects dormitories and scarce habitat.
Wind turbines and lightning also pose a threat, along with fly-killing papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo tracking technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight trajectory.
NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained specialists who regularly carry out studies, inspections of dormitories and sometimes rescues.
It also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats at Threave property in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The property’s director, David Thompson, says it’s the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
“We have the old buildings, lots of veteran trees and all this good habitat.
However, there’s still a lot about bats that we don’t know about, so the work we’ve done here and on other properties will help us know more about what they need to flourish.”
It was emphasized by him the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance on the properties, because the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dorm can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dormitories.
Elisabeth Ferrell, head of the Scottish Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we simply don’t know how their populations are avenging.”
